"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824449","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-01-22","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by Parliamentary Under Secretary of State, Steve Baker, to written parliamentary question 122345.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2018-01-22T16:05:37.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824449/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824449/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-01-17","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 16 January 2018 to Question 121433, for what reasons no reference was made to the Market Access team in his Department.","false","Biography information for Jo Platt","Leigh","Jo Platt","123250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824450","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-22","<p>The UK is proud to support the Africa-led movement to end FGM, which has been instrumental in achieving the significant decline of the practice seen in recent decades – in 1985, 51% of girls around the world aged 15-19 had undergone FGM; today the figure is 37%. We are a global leader on this issue, having made the largest ever donor commitment to ending FGM, and we have galvanised others to take action of their own through our international Girl Summit.</p><p>We continue to support and accelerate the Africa-led movement, and encourage others to step up too, because if current trends in population growth continue the number of girls undergoing FGM will rise significantly over the next 15 years. Support from the UK has been critical to progress so far; in the last three years alone over 18 million people across 16 countries have publically pledged to abandon the practice, two more countries (Nigeria and the Gambia) have made the practice illegal and the largest ever collective of African organisations tackling FGM (600+) has come together to accelerate the Africa-led movement to end the practice.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2018-01-22T18:06:20.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824450/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824450/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-17","Africa: Female Genital Mutilation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what progress has been made on eliminating female genital mutilation (FGM) since the Africa-led movement on FGM was established.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","123251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824451","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>We are aware of reports of the demolition of this place of Christian worship and my officials continue to monitor such incidents closely. We have not discussed this specific incident with the Chinese authorities.</p><p>We remain concerned about restrictions on freedom of religion or belief in China and reports of the destruction of places of worship. We raised our concerns over restrictions on freedom of religion or belief directly with the Chinese authorities at the UK-China Human Rights Dialogue in Beijing on 27 June 2017. We also issued an Item IV statement at the 35th UN Human Rights Council in the same month reiterating our concerns. We will continue to raise these concerns about human rights with the Chinese authorities at every opportunity.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2018-01-22T17:14:58.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824451/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824451/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-01-17","China: Christianity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will make representations to the Chinese Government on the demolition of the Golden Lampstand Protestant Church in Linfen City, China, in early January 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","123252"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824452","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-22","<p>All 32 of the Government’s strategic suppliers whom we targeted in 2015 had signed up to the Prompt Payment Code by July 2017, promising to pay suppliers, including small businesses in their supply chain, promptly and fairly.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/prompt-payment-code-signatories" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/prompt-payment-code-signatories</a></p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-01-22T17:26:55.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824452/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824452/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-17","Government Departments: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many Government strategic suppliers are signed up to the prompt payment code.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824453","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>The number of staff working (by Full Time Equivalent) on monitoring the delivery of contracts for prison maintenance by private sector companies is as follows:</p><p>a) 2015: 95</p><p>b) 2016: 98</p><p>c) 2017: 97</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T15:36:39.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824453/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824453/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824453/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-17","Prisons: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many staff in his Department worked on monitoring the delivery of contracts for prison maintenance by private sector companies in (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","123254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824454","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>Staffing costs for the teams in the Department with responsibility for monitoring the delivery of contracts for prison maintenance by private sector companies is as follows:</p><ol><li>2015: £2,491k</li><li>2016: £4,471k</li><li>2017: £4,438k</li></ol><p>Please note that the Amey and Carillion prison maintenance contracts didn’t commence delivery until June 2015.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T18:05:35.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824454/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824454/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-17","Prisons: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the staffing cost was for teams in his Department with responsibility for monitoring the delivery of contracts for prison maintenance by private sector companies in (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","123255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824455","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>Representatives of the Department at all levels involved in the monitoring of delivery of contracts for prison maintenance meet with Carillion on a frequent basis. This includes weekly meetings at an operational site level through to at least monthly meetings at a leadership level. Leadership teams also met to discuss specific issues and such meetings have been more frequent over the past 18 months. We do not hold a record of the number of total number of meetings.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T15:37:21.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824455/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824455/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824455/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-17","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times representatives from his Department met with representatives of Carillion to discuss contracts for prison maintenance in (a) 2016 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","123256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824456","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>Formal concerns about issues with the delivery of the contract were are issued through the Early Warning Notice and Defect provisions as laid out in the NEC3 standard form of contract which is employed for prison maintenance. A formal letter of concern was issued in 2016 to advise Carillion of performance failures. A performance action plan was put in place to address these failings and some improvements were made. This process was subsequently subsumed into a wider service improvement initiative.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T15:39:10.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824456/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824456/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824456/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-17","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times his Department issued letters of concern to Carillion on its delivery of contracts for prison maintenance in (a) 2016 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","123257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824457","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>There are no plans to place a copy in the library of any reports produced by the MoJ on the effectiveness of the delivery of contracts by Carillion for prison maintenance works.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T17:59:22.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824457/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824457/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824457/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-17","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will place a copy in the Library of any reports produced by his Department on the effectiveness of the delivery of contracts by Carillion for prison maintenance works in (a) 2016 and (b) 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","123258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824458","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Department has been undertaking a significant continuous improvement initiative in collaboration with both Carillion and Amey since May 2017. The aim was to make improvements to the systems, processes and practices that exist within the FM environment of prisons to deliver service and productivity improvements. To date no changes to contracts have been made as a consequence of this initiative</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T15:41:43.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824458/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824458/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824458/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-17","Prisons: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what changes to contracts were agreed between his Department and private sector companies contracted to provide prison maintenance after his Department confirmed in July 2017 that the contracts would not deliver the savings budgeted for.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","123259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824459","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>There was an underestimation of the historical costs of maintenance and services, which meant that more of the award has been spent on maintenance and services rather than efficiency savings. We assess the major elements of financial risk within the contract lie in asset verification, asset condition, service verification and variable costs. Actions have been taken within each area. They have ensured clarity on financial risk and have allowed negotiated settlements to be reached that reflect true contractual costs. Appropriate governance has been put in place that ensures that variable costs are accurately reported and justified and that claims are assured by the Contract Management team. Governors are focused on the management and reduction of vandalism and damage within their establishments supporting this cost reduction. All actions and improved contract management assurance has ensured that historic and future additional costs are accurate and appropriate.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T18:00:11.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824459/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824459/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824459/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-17","Prisons: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what assessment his Department has made of the reasons that the contracts with private sector companies to deliver prison maintenance did not achieve the savings budgeted for as announced by his Department in July 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","123260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824460","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>Steering Groups were held initially weekly and then fortnightly between HMPPS and Carillion Leadership to track and monitor their improvement plan, and were attended by Senior Leaders across the department.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T15:42:19.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824460/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824460/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824460/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-17","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many meetings were held with Carillion and his Department to discuss the plan agreed with Carillion to improve their delivery of prison maintenance services between September 2016 and February 2017.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","123261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824461","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-01-25","<p>An independent review of the service was undertaken in early 2017 which was used to support several improvement initiatives. There are no plans to place the information in the library as the report contains commercially sensitive information.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2018-01-25T15:42:52.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824461/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824461/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824461/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-01-17","Prisons: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what research his Department has undertaken into the effectiveness of prison maintenance services being carried out in House, and if he will place that research in the Library.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","123262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824462","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-22","<p>Plymouth has received Coastal Communities Fund grants worth £2.67 million for two projects since 2013: £670,000 in 2013 for the regeneration of Plymouth’s waterfront; and £2 million in 2017 to create new and refurbish existing cultural and heritage venues in the city.</p><p>I announced on 4 September last year that Coastal Communities Fund Round 5 will open for applications early this year with at least £40 million of funding available.</p><p>Hon Members with coastal constituencies should encourage prospective applicants to make an early start in developing their plans for revitalising their local communities.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-01-22T16:51:52.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824462/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824462/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-17","Coastal Communities Fund: Plymouth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to ensure that coastal areas in and around Plymouth receive an equitable share of funding from the Coastal Communities Fund.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","123263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824463","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-01-23","<p>Plymouth has received Coastal Community Fund grants worth £2.67 million for two projects since 2013: £670,000 in 2013 for the regeneration of Plymouth’s waterfront; and £2 million in 2017 for create new and refurbish existing cultural and heritage venues in Plymouth.</p><p>Funding is determined through a competitive bid-led process based on demonstrating the strongest fit with the programme's outcomes and criteria.</p><p>The next bidding round is due to open shortly and will give all coastal communities another opportunity to bid for funds.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2018-01-23T13:37:21.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824463/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824463/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-01-17","Coastal Areas: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government,  how much funding his Department has allocated to projects in (a) Plymouth and (b) South West Devon constituency from the Coastal Communities Fund in each year for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","123264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824464","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-22","<p>According to Ofcom's recently published 2017 Connected Nations report, 38% of premises have bought superfast connections that receive more than 30Mbps as of May 2017. This is up from 31% in 2016.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-22T16:46:49.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824464/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824464/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-17","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate his Department has made of the proportion of homes receiving broadband speeds of 24mbps or more as of 31 December 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","123265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824465","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-22","<p>The costs of consulting on s40 of the Crime and Courts Act 2013 and Part 2 of the Leveson Inquiry have all been met from existing departmental budgets.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2018-01-22T16:50:09.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824465/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824465/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824465/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-17","Mass Media: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what estimate he has made of the total spend from the public purse to date of consulting on section 40 of the Crime and Courts Act 2013 and Part 2 of the Leveson Inquiry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","123266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824466","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-22","<p>The current consultation on proposals for changes to gaming machines and social responsibility measures closes on 23 January. The Government will publish its response in due course.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-01-22T16:15:38.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824466/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824466/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-17","Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility Measures Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, when his Department plans to publish its response to the consultation on proposals for changes to gaming machines and social responsibility measures after the consultation closes on 23 January 2018.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","123267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824467","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-22","<p>There are strict controls on the content of all gambling advertisements, including broadcast adverts, and they must not be targeted at children. Gambling operators who advertise in the UK must comply with the advertising codes, which aim to ensure gambling advertising does not appeal particularly to children or young people or exploit vulnerable people. TV adverts must be pre-cleared by Clearcast and the Advertising Standards Authority (ASA) acts on complaints and proactively checks the media to take action against misleading, harmful or offensive advertisements.</p><p> </p><p>The Gambling Industry Code for Socially Responsible Advertising bans free sign up offers targeted at new customers before 9pm and the website address for GambleAware must remain on the screen for at least 10% of an advert’s length. All TV and print adverts must carry an 18+ or ‘no under 18s’ message, except for lotteries, where the equivalent age is 16. Operators’ logos must not appear on any commercial merchandising which is designed for children, including replica football shirts in children’s sizes.</p><p> </p><p>The Gaming Machines and Social Responsibility consultation, published on 31st October, outlines a package of measures to further strengthen protections on advertising, including a major responsible gambling advertising campaign, funded by broadcasters and industry. This is proposed to include TV adverts, including around live sport, as well as radio, cinema, print and online. In addition, the Committees of Advertising Practice intend to publish new guidance to protect those at risk of problem gambling as well as children and young people, and the Gambling Commission will be consulting on increasing sanctions available where operators breach the codes.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2018-01-22T16:10:56.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824467/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824467/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-17","Gambling: Advertising","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what his policy is on the appropriateness of the prevalence of gambling adverts across sports broadcasts; and if he will make statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","123268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824468","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-22","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy and the Department for International Trade have actively supported the Global Vehicle Trust (GVT) in seeking investors and manufacturing partners. This support included helping arrange for the OX to be displayed at the Low Carbon Vehicle show at Millbrook, Bedfordshire in 2016, and introducing GVT to potential international partners at the show; and discussions in 2017 between our Post in India and potential local partners.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-01-22T16:14:40.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824468/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824468/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824468/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-17","Motor Vehicles: Developing Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department has had discussions with the Global Vehicle Trust on government support for a UK manufacturing base for the Ox flat-packed truck for the developing world.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","123269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824469","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-24","<p>To date, DFID has had 1 meeting with Global Vehicle Trust to discuss the Ox flat-packed truck (in November 2016).</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-24T17:24:08.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824469/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824469/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-17","Developing Countries: Motor Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether her Department has had discussions with the Global Vehicle Trust on the use of the Ox flat-packed truck for the developing world for UK aid projects.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","123270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824470","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Department has not made any assessment of the cost of responding to subject access requests under the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).</p><p> </p><p>The United Kingdom is reviewing its data protection legislation in light of the GDPR. The Data Protection Bill is currently going through Parliament. Once it is enacted it will become the new Data Protection Act. It will implement the GDPR from May 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Article 12(5) of the GDPR refers to the rights of the data subject when requesting their information and that this is provided free of charge. Data controllers that process personal data will be required to comply with subject access requests in this way.</p><p> </p><p>There are provisions in the GDPR and the Data Protection Bill, as there are currently under the Data Protection Act 1998, to charge or refuse a request should it be considered manifestly unreasonable or repeated. However, these should be considered on a case by case basis and considered in line with guidance provided by the Information Commissioner’s Office.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2018-01-25T14:38:31.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824470/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824470/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-17","NHS: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of the requirement to respond to subject access requests free of charge after 25 May 2018 under the General Data Protection Regulation for (a) Acute Trusts (b), Mental Health Trusts, (c) GP practices and (d) the NHS as a whole.","false","Biography information for Kate Green","Stretford and Urmston","Kate Green","123271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824471","Department for International Trade","false","2018-01-25","<p>My Department has actively supported the Global Vehicle Trust (GVT) in promoting the OX, and in seeking investors and manufacturing partners. This support included helping arrange for the OX to be displayed at the Low Carbon Vehicle show at Millbrook, Bedfordshire in 2016, and introducing GVT to potential international partners at the show; and discussions in 2017 between our Post in India and potential local partners. My Department continues to offer its support to this project.</p>","Beverley and Holderness","Graham Stuart",,"2018-01-25T16:20:47.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824471/answer","Biography information for Graham Stuart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824471/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-01-17","Developing Countries: Motor Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether his Department has had discussions with the Global Vehicle Trust on export support for the Ox flat-packed truck for the developing world.","false","Biography information for Stephen Kerr","Stirling","Stephen Kerr","123272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824472","Department for International Development","false","2018-01-22","<p>The UK has been at the forefront of international efforts to end Child, Early and Forced Marriage since hosting the Girl Summit in 2014. DFID focuses on the causes and consequences of child marriage, recognising many instances of child marriage are forced marriages.</p><p>The main UK Aid-funded programme to prevent and respond to child, early and forced marriage, Accelerating Action Against Child Marriage, includes UNICEF, UNFPA and civil society organisations. The programme has reached over 1.6 million people. This includes three quarters of a million girls at risk of child marriage, or already married; as well as community members and leaders who influence practices and behaviours around child marriage. UKAid funds totalled £4.1m in 2015, £11.3m in 2016, and £9.4m by end of the 2017/18 financial year.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-01-22T17:46:38.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824472/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824472/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-01-17","Developing Countries: Forced Marriage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what funding her Department provided to organisations fighting or giving assistance to people affected by forced and illegal marriage in (a) 2015, (b) 2016 and (c) 2017.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Sir Mark Hendrick","123273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824473","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Prime Minister established the post of Special Envoy for the Mayflower commemorations in the Spring Budget of 2017 and invited Oliver Colvile to take up the position. Following the 2017 General Election, the Prime Minister invited Mr Colvile to continue in the role, which he accepted.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Northampton North","Michael Ellis",,"2018-01-25T12:28:14.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824473/answer","Biography information for Michael Ellis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824473/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-01-17","Mayflower: Anniversaries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what steps he is taking to appoint a special representative for the Mayflower 400 celebrations in 2020; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","123274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824474","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-01-23","<p>The table below shows the number of Motor Neurone Disease (MND) claimants who were awarded Personal Independence Payment (PIP) between 6th April 2016 and 5<sup>th</sup> April 2017 with a 10 year review split by Mobility and Daily Living components of PIP.</p><p> </p><p><em>Table: PIP Daily living and Mobility component awards made between 6<sup>th</sup> April 2016 and 5<sup>th</sup> April 2017 for MND claimants with a “light-touch” review after 10 years.</em></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Enhanced Daily Living</p></td><td><p>Standard Daily Living</p></td><td><p>Nil Daily Living</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Enhanced Mobility</p></td><td><p>170</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Standard Mobility</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nil Mobility</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>#</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: PIP ADS</p><p>Figures are based on the first outcome recorded for each case and include both new claims and DLA reassessment claims assessed under normal rules. Data has been rounded to the nearest 10 cases; totals less than 5 but greater than 0 are indicated by “#”. This is unpublished data and it should be used with caution and it may be subject to future revision. Data is based on main disabling condition as recorded on the PIP computer system. Claimants may often have multiple disabling conditions upon which the decision is based but only the primary condition is shown in these statistics.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-01-23T13:26:05.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824474/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824474/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-01-17","Personal Independence Payment: Motor Neurone Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with motor neurone disease awarded personal independence payments in 2016-17 were granted an ongoing award with a light-touch review after 10 years by (a) mobility and daily living components and (b) standard and enhanced awards.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","123275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824475","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy identified £1.2 billion that may be invested in cycling and walking between 2016/17 to 2020/21. Many of the decisions on the allocation of these funds will be made by the relevant local body in line with the Government’s devolution and localism agenda.</p><p> </p><p>The tables below provide a guide to the funding allocated in 2017/18 to Plymouth and Devon identified in the Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Plymouth City Council</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Funding programme</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Access Fund</p></td><td><p>0.499</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Integrated Transport Block*</p></td><td><p>0.291</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bikeability (national cycling training)</p></td><td><p>0.142</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>0.932</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Devon County Council</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Funding programme</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>£m</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Access Fund</p></td><td><p>0.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Integrated Transport Block*</p></td><td><p>0.540</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Bikeability (national cycling training)</p></td><td><p>0.280</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>1.32</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department is also providing technical support to Plymouth City Council to assist with the development of their Local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plan. The level of support has yet to be determined. The Heart of the South West Local Enterprise Partnership has allocated £18.330m to cycling and walking projects between 2016/17 and 2020/21.**</p><p> </p><p>*This is based on a survey of Local Transport Authorities published by the Department in February 2016 revealed that 11% of this fund supports cycling schemes and 4% supports streetscape and Rights of Way schemes.</p><p>** This is based on self-reported data received from the Local Enterprise Partnership.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-01-25T11:01:43.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824475/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824475/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-17","Cycling and Walking: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department has allocated to (a) Plymouth and (b) Devon for projects relating to his Department's cycling and walking investment strategy in the financial year 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","123276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824476","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-23","<p>The Secretary of State regularly meets with stakeholders from across the rail industry, including Network Rail. Such discussions may include reference to rail services in the South West.</p><p> </p><p>Officials from the Department for Transport have met with Network Rail to discuss how the findings of the Speed to the West study might be considered as part of the planning process for Control Period 6 (2019 – 2024).</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-23T15:10:01.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824476/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824476/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-17","Railways","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with Network Rail on the Speed to the West initiative in the last three months; and what the outcomes of those discussions has been.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","123277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824477","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-23","<p>We will continue to engage with the Peninsula Rail Task Force (PRTF) and other interested parties as the planning for Network Rail’s work programme for the period starting in April 2019 and the development of the specifications for the future Great Western and Cross Country franchises unfold.</p><p> </p><p>The work of the Peninsula Rail Task Force continues to be a valuable part of the process for defining our priorities for investment after 2019.</p><p> </p><p>New enhancements will be taken forward through a new process in the form of a pipeline, designed to ensure investment best addresses the needs of passengers and freight, and that funding commitments appropriately reflect the stage of development of enhancements.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-23T15:13:41.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824477/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824477/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824477/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-17","Railways: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to respond to the Peninsula Rail Task Force rail improvement plan published in 2016.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","123278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824478","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-23","<p>Network Rail are preparing Strategic Business Plans for Control Period 6 (CP6) as part of their regulated Periodic Review process, expected to be concluded in October 2018. This will determine the level of investment in operations, maintenance and renewals for each route across the network, including the Western Route, which contains the line from Paddington to Penzance.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-01-23T15:16:44.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824478/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824478/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-17","Railways: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much his Department and Network Rail plan to spend on the Paddington to Penzance rail link in Control Period 6.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","123279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824479","Department for Education","false","2018-01-22","<p>Following the announcement on the 15 January 2018 regarding the liquidation of Carillion, the Education and Skills Funding Agency (ESFA) has enacted robust contingency plans and identified the Construction Industry Training Board, (CITB) as the best placed alternative provider.</p><p> </p><p>The ESFA contacted all affected apprentices on 15/01/18 to notify them of the situation and next steps. The Study Programme Learners were notified by letter on the 17/01/2018. Affected learners have been provided with the details of a dedicated mailbox: <a href="mailto:Carillion.Construction@education.gov.uk" target="_blank">Carillion.Construction@education.gov.uk</a> - where they can raise any issues or concerns.</p><p> </p><p>The CITB is on the ESFA’s register of approved apprenticeship training providers; it delivers good quality provision, with a proven track record of delivering the specific frameworks and standards that current Carillion Apprentices are studying. CITB centres are geographically situated, within what is anticipated to be a reasonable travel time for the apprentices; and critically they have the capacity and capability to take on displaced apprentices and study programme learners. A dedicated team of 50 advisers and assessors in the CITB has been identified to support apprentices and work with them to identify new employers.</p><p> </p><p>The CITB is utilising its existing employer contacts in the sector and the grant incentives it has available, in order to find and secure alternative employers for the apprentices to complete their frameworks or standards. Additionally, it is making direct contact with Carillion supply chain companies. CITB have reported that numerous employers have responded positively with offers of support.</p><p> </p><p>CITB have contacted all affected learners to begin the transfer process, with a focus on minimising disruption to the learner and their learner journey. It has established a dedicated helpline to support those affected and has scheduled a series of workshops for learners, which will take place in the regions of the 11 Carillion Training Centres. Those workshops will provide advice on next steps and offer one to one support as required. The timings and locations of these events have been communicated to the learners through telephone calls, email and a comprehensive social media campaign.</p><p> </p><p>Carillion has also issued communication to its learners, alerting them to the situation and reassuring them, that support is in place to ensure a swift transition.</p><p> </p><p>The ESFA is meeting with CITB daily to monitor progress and resolve any issues.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-01-22T17:50:12.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824479/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824479/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-17","Carillion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of Carillion entering liquidation on training and apprenticeships in the construction industry.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","123280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824480","Department for Education","false","2018-01-22","<p>All Carillion apprentices are employed by Carillion Construction. The department is working with the Construction Industry Training Board (CITB) to find alternative employers for those apprentices to complete their apprenticeships. No apprentices have had their employment contract with Carillion Construction terminated by the Insolvency Service.</p><p> </p><p>Learners attending Carillion training centres, who are funded through a study programme will continue to receive training and this will be delivered by CITB or their partner colleges.</p><p> </p><p>The CITB are utilising their existing employer contacts in the sector and the grant incentives they have available. To find and secure alternative employers for the apprentices to complete their frameworks or standards. Additionally, they are making direct contact with companies in Carillion’s supply chain. CITB have reported that numerous employers have responded positively with offers of support.</p><p> </p><p>The CITB have contacted all affected learners to begin the transfer process, with a focus on minimising disruption to the learner and their learner journey. They have established a dedicated helpline to support those affected and have scheduled a series of workshops for learners, which will take place in the regions of the 11 Carillion Training Centres. These workshops will provide advice on next steps and offer 1 to 1 support as required. The timings and locations of these events have been communicated to the learners through telephone calls, email and a comprehensive social media campaign. Carillion are also actively encouraging their learners to attend these regional events.</p><p> </p><p>The Education and Skills Funding Agency (ESFA) are meeting with CITB daily to monitor progress and resolve issues.</p><p> </p><p>The ESFA funds training providers for their delivery of apprenticeships in arrears, so payments made have been calculated based on the activity recorded by Carillion and returned to the ESFA in monthly Individual learner records.</p><p>Normal ESFA audit requirements will continue to apply and there must be evidence of participation in learning for funds to be earned. We will reconcile payments when the liquidator makes a final claim for training delivered by Carillion.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","123518 ; 123519","2018-01-22T17:52:57.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824480/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824480/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-17","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many building industry related training schemes and apprenticeships provided directly by Carillion and/or subcontracted companies have been terminated ahead of completion.","false","Biography information for Melanie Onn","Great Grimsby","Melanie Onn","123281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824481","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-01-25","<p>Community-based services, which include minor injuries units, urgent treatment centres and minor injury services provided by general practitioners and pharmacists, play an important role in making sure people can access the appropriate services when and where they need them.</p><p> </p><p>Minor injury units (MIUs) across Cornwall have treated over 86,000 people during the past financial year and during the last three months, MIUs in the Cornwall area have treated nearly 25,000 patients. Of those, just over 3,000 were treated at St Austell and just over 1,500 at Newquay.</p><p> </p><p>Cornwall Partnership NHS Foundation Trust has a protocol in place which enables resources to be shared between St Austell and Newquay MIUs. In addition, partnership arrangements are in place between the National Health Service and the local council to use the Better Care Fund to provide a range of services including: generic support workers; improved community bed capacity, and more flexible and responsive domiciliary care to ensure that patient assessments and re-ablement are carried out in the most appropriate, out-of-hospital setting.</p><p> </p><p>Locally, the NHS has extensively promoted the use of all community based services, including support from pharmacists, self-care and the importance of having the flu jab.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-01-25T14:32:25.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824481/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824481/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-01-17","Minor Injuries Units: Cornwall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to utilise the role of NHS minor injury units in (a) St. Austell and (b) Newquay to reduce pressures on A&E departments in Cornwall.","false","Biography information for Steve Double","St Austell and Newquay","Steve Double","123282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824482","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-01-24","<p>We have not had recent discussions with local authorities about increases in the urban fox population.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-01-24T15:13:37.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824482/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824482/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-01-17","Foxes: Urban Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether he has had discussions with local authorities on increases in the urban fox population; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","123283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824483","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-22","<p>Consistent with the Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015, the Army plans to establish two Strike brigades. The Strike brigades will offer increased operational agility and responsiveness to Defence. For a recent update on the progress towards establishing this capability, I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave her on 11 December 2017 to Question 117878.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2018-01-22T17:50:20.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824483/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824483/answer","Hansard Extract  11 December 2017  HOC 117878.docx","Hansard Extract  11 December 2017  HOC 117878.docx","117878 - WQnA extract on the Army","117878 - WQnA extract on the Army","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824483/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-17","Army","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department still plans to establish two Strike Brigades.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","123284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824484","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-25","<p>With reference to the National Shipbuilding Strategy no Departmental objective has been set for the export of 40 Type 31e frigates. The Government has assessed that there is a potential light frigate market of around 40 ships over the next 10 years.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-25T16:57:11.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824484/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824484/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-17","Type 31 Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the National Shipbuilding Strategy, what the evidential basis is for his Department's decision to set the objective of exporting 40 Type 31e frigates.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","123285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824485","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-22","<p>At this stage in the liquidation process it is far too soon for the Liquidator to have gathered in full details of the company’s debts and creditors. The Liquidation process for such a complex and interconnected group of companies will take some time. The Official Receiver and his Special Managers have access to the records of the company and will be analysing these as quickly as possible.</p><p>We have taken steps to minimise job losses by enacting robust contingency plans to mitigate the impact of Carillion’s insolvency on public services and the individuals employed by the company. PWC are acting as Special Manager to the Official Receiver to ensure that we can continue to provide public services until the liquidation is complete, this means people providing these services can continue to go to work and be confident that they will get paid.</p><p>We met with and sought assurance from major high street lenders that they will not penalise small businesses affected by Carillion’s liquidation. Lenders are contacting customers and, where appropriate, are putting in place emergency measures, including overdraft extensions, payment holidays and fee waivers to ensure those facing short term issues can be helped to stay on track.</p><p>Government undertook to fund for 48 hours the costs of Carillion continuing to deliver purely private contracts in order to give private sector contractors to determine whether they want to pay for continuation of services from Carillion in liquidation while they move their contracts to another firm.</p><p>Between 15 and 16 January all of the company’s private sector service customers have been contacted by the Official Receiver to determine their ongoing needs. Over 90% of these customers have indicated that they want Carillion to continue providing services in the interim until new suppliers can be found and will provide funding which enables the Official Receiver to retain the employees working on those contracts.</p><p>My rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy chaired the first meeting on 18 January of a taskforce to advise on the impact on small businesses and employees affected by Carillion insolvency. It will act as a means for government to communicate to those affected by Carillion’s liquidation, assess wider economic impacts and consider how to ensure that employees are provided with the right support to maximise rapid re-employment.</p><p>Information is published online by the Insolvency Service for employees, creditors and suppliers affected and seeking advice. This can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/carillion-declares-insolvency-information-for-employees-creditors-and-suppliers" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/carillion-declares-insolvency-information-for-employees-creditors-and-suppliers</a>.</p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-22T15:58:01.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824485/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824485/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-17","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate the Government has made of the number of companies affected by the liquidation of Carillion; and what steps the Government plans to take to minimise job losses at those companies.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","123286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824486","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-01-22","<p>The nature of Carillion business means that it sub-contracts significant proportions of its work, with the potential for those sub-contractors to sub-contract out further elements. The complexity of the contracting structure is such that it is not possible for Government at this stage in the liquidation process to have an estimate of the number of jobs at risk in Carillion’s supply chain.</p><p> </p>","Burton","Andrew Griffiths",,"2018-01-22T18:00:17.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824486/answer","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824486/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-01-17","Carillion: Insolvency","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the number of jobs at risk in Carillion's supply chain.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","123287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824487","Cabinet Office","false","2018-02-01","<p>The Government’s priority is to ensure the continued delivery of public services, and we have contingency plans in place to ensure this happens. We routinely stress-test contracts to ensure that if one party within a contract fails to deliver, the other parties involved will step in to complete the work.</p><p>The majority of public procurement is governed by Public Contracts Regulations. These stipulate that public procurers have to award contracts through fair and open competition, in line with principles of equal treatment, transparency and non-discrimination. Suppliers have to meet certain criteria to be able to bid for public contracts, including a minimum level of financial and economic standing proven through turnover, audited accounts or other financial measures.</p><p>Given that a large number of companies issue profit warnings from time to time, it is unrealistic to terminate all business with such a company as this would further undermine chances of company recovery</p><p>Once Carillion had made the profit warnings, we took steps to ensure that greater degrees of protection were built into the small number of specific contracts that were awarded after July last year.</p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-02-01T14:18:36.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824487/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824487/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-17","Government Departments: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the Government's policy is on awarding contracts to companies which have issued profit warnings.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","123288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824488","Cabinet Office","false","2018-02-27","<p>The list of Cabinet Committees and Implementation Task Forces, including the membership and terms of reference, are regularly published on Gov.uk. An updated list was published on 1<sup>st</sup> February 2018. The list can be found here: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-cabinet-committees-system-and-list-of-cabinet-committees</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2018-02-27T11:19:37.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824488/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824488/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-17","David Lidington","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, which Cabinet committees and sub-committees he (a) chairs and (b) attends.","false","Biography information for Emma Reynolds","Wolverhampton North East","Emma Reynolds","123289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824489","Department for Transport","false","2018-01-25","<p>It is for the House to agree any instruction to the Select Committee which will consider the High Speed Rail (West Midlands – Crewe) Bill and there is a motion on the order paper which relates to that instruction. Furthermore, we have recently consulted on proposals for a Crewe Hub and expect to publish our response shortly.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-01-25T15:00:59.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824489/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824489/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-01-17","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what guidelines on the remit of the HS2 Phase 2a Bill he plans to provide the Select Committee about the Crewe Hub.","false","Biography information for Laura Smith","Crewe and Nantwich","Laura Smith","123290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824490","HM Treasury","false","2018-01-25","<p>The 2017 edition of the annual data on Private Finance Initiative and Private Finance 2 contracts will be released very soon.</p>","Newark","Robert Jenrick",,"2018-01-25T14:41:39.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824490/answer","Biography information for Robert Jenrick","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824490/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2018-01-17","Public Private Partnerships: Disclosure of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to update his Department's transparency release entitled Private Finance Initiative and Private Finance 2 projects.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824491","Cabinet Office","false","2018-01-23","<p>Suppliers on Crown Commercial Service frameworks are published publicly on the CCS website:</p><p><a href="https://ccs-agreements.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/suppliers" target="_blank">https://ccs-agreements.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/suppliers</a></p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2018-01-23T15:21:01.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824491/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824491/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-01-17","Crown Commercial Service: Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many Crown Commercial Service contracts there are with Government strategic suppliers.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","123292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824492","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-22","<p>The Strategic Defence and Security Review 2015 allocated £60 million to further optimise a Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carrier to better meet the demands of the Landing Platform Helicopter role. This includes communications systems for amphibious operations, improving the domestic services in the aircraft carrier for Royal Marines, providing ammunition storage, increasing the number of helicopter operating spots and expanding the operating capacity for helicopters.</p><p>The Department will continue to explore a variety of options to augment both Queen Elizabeth Class aircraft carriers with these capabilities in the future.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-22T17:49:06.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824492/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824492/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-17","HMS Queen Elizabeth","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister for the Armed Forces of 23 October 2017, Official Report, column 15, what enhancements the Government plans to make to the Queen Elizabeth class carriers to support the UK's amphibious capability; how much he estimates the cost of those enhancements to be; and when those enhancements will be delivered.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","123293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824493","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-24","<p>The Ministry of Defence has implemented a robust governance process for the delivery of the £7.4 billion efficiency target from the 2015 Spending Review. We are committed to delivering the target in full and good progress has been made. We are forecasting 'line of sight' to 90% of the £7.4 billion target over the Spending Review Period (2020-21) and all savings are being reinvested in the Defence budget.</p>","South Staffordshire","Gavin Williamson",,"2018-01-24T16:11:29.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824493/answer","Biography information for Gavin Williamson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824493/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-17","Ministry of Defence: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps his Department is taking to improve methodology for accounting for and attributing savings more accurately.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","123294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824494","Department for Education","false","2018-01-25","<p>As with other areas of the public sector, the department will be monitoring the uptake of apprenticeships by the school workforce. Public sector bodies included in the apprenticeship target are required to annually publish and report to the department their progress towards the target. The first reports (covering the period 1 April 2017 – 31 March 2018) are due on 30 September 2018. As we have outlined to the Public Accounts Committee, the department will also include the financial impact of the apprenticeship levy as part of our publication regarding the cost pressures on schools.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-01-25T17:28:24.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824494/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824494/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-01-17","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the effect of the apprenticeship levy on schools in (a) Devon and Plymouth and (b) England; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","123295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824495","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-25","<p>Informed by Sir John Parker's independent report, the National Shipbuilding Strategy concluded that that there was a competitive market for Type 31e. The use of competition remains the cornerstone of Defence procurement as a means of driving innovation and industrial performance and providing value for money for the taxpayer.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-25T16:58:10.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824495/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824495/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-17","Type 31 Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the answer given by his Department’s Permanent Secretary to question 45 in evidence to the Public Accounts Committee on Wednesday 10 January 2018, HC 723, what the evidential basis is for efficiencies being produced by adopting the procurement model outlined in the National Shipbuilding Strategy for the Type 31 frigate.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","123296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824496","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-22","<p>The information requested is available at the following link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-armed-forces-equipment-and-formations-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/uk-armed-forces-equipment-and-formations-2017</a></p><p> </p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-22T17:53:38.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824496/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824496/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-17","Warships","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many (a) submarines, (b) Royal Navy surface fleet vessels and (c) Royal Fleet Auxiliary vessels there have been in the UK Armed Forces in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","123297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824497","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-25","<p>The National Shipbuilding Strategy makes clear that all non-warships, which includes the Fleet Solid Support vessels, will be subject to international competition.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-25T16:51:58.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824497/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824497/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-17","Royal Fleet Auxiliary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department plans to treat fleet solid support ships as warships for tendering purposes.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","123298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824498","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Warrior Capability Sustainment Programme is in the Demonstration Phase. A prototype vehicle has already undergone initial live firing and a rigorous trials programme will start shortly.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-25T17:29:55.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824498/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824498/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-17","Warrior Armoured Vehicle","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the status of the Warrior Capability and Sustainment Programme is.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","123299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824499","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Supplier Portal is delivered by our service provider as part of a concession contract. The content of the portal is maintained by the Ministry of Defence's Supply Chain Development team, consisting of four people, as part of its wider remit to provide supplier outreach activities.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-25T16:59:10.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824499/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824499/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-17","Defence: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to Industry for Defence and a Prosperous Britain: Refreshing Defence Industrial Policy, published on 20 December 2017, what is the budget is for the Supplier Portal and how many people are employed for the Supplier Portal.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","123300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824500","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-01-25","<p>The Ministry of Defence's Acquisition System Guidance contains significant guidance and examples of good practice on how to engage effectively with SMEs. This guidance is reinforced with specific SME content on internal training courses and through periodic coverage in internal newsletters and other publications.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2018-01-25T17:00:15.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824500/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/824500/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-01-17","Defence: Industry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to Industry for Defence and a Prosperous Britain: Refreshing Defence Industrial Policy, published on 20 December 2017, what internal guidance his Department has on engaging potential SME suppliers.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","123301"
